<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">RPG<h3>
  <p>Role-playing games often feature a protagonist who starts off as weak and
  gradually makes progress or becomes stronger throughout the game. These games have
very few boundaries and can be based within any setting imaginable. RPG's usually incorporate
great amounts of customization, in order to provide players with their own personalized in-game
experience.</p>
<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">Platformer<h3>
  <p>Platform games, also referred to as "jump n' run" games, are usually characterized
  by navigation through multi-layered courses. Players must jump, run, avoid obstacles,
and survive antagonists, while simultaneously attempting to reach the end of the level.
Checkpoints are common in these games to prevent loss of progress points if the player falls
off the stage or loses too many lives.</p>
<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">Racing</h3>
  <p>In racing games, the player finds themself behind the wheel. Settings might include
  all kinds of tracks and vehicles. There are no real rules other than speeding through the course
from start to finish while attempting to be the first to reach the finish line. Many games add obstacles
or items that can be used to slow down other racers.</p>
<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">Action/Adventure</h3>
  <p>The Action-Adventure genre is incredibly inclusive, due to it being hybrid in nature.
  Many argue that it is the broadest genre. One thing is for certain, though: any games
including both components of action (whether it be between NPCs or other players) and adventure
are a good fit for this genre.</p>
<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">Fighting</h3>
  <p>Traditional fighting games usually feature the main player facing off against
  another player, or even an NPC (non-playable character). Over time, fighting games
have grown to support multiple opponents simultaneously, creating exciting simulations
that leverage the many shapes and forms of combat.</p>
<h3 style="margin-left:40px;">FPS</h3>
